<TITLE> China to stick to tougher routines for Olympics-coach </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, Sept 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - China's head coach has defended the national team's performance at the world championships and said it would continue to produce more complex routines ahead of the Beijing Olympics next year. Having won a record eight golds at the 2006 world championships in Aarhus, China managed only five in Stuttgart earlier this month. China's women stumbled in complex routines and were largely outclassed by a resurgent United States. Coach Huang Yubin brushed off the team's lower medal tally and said errors that cost world titles were welcome ahead of the 2008 Games. "In terms of our Olympic preparations, mistakes help us to summarise our advantages and highlight our weaknesses," Huang told Tuesday's Beijing Morning Post. "Our team is in better shape than it was a year ago as far as the Olympics are concerned." Huang said China would continue to raise the difficulty of its routines, the complexity of which has often given their gymnasts higher start values than opponents, preventing the odd tumble from seriously harming final scores. "As to raising difficulty levels, there is only one way forward as there are no boundaries placed on difficulty in gymnastics," Huang said. "It can be seen from the past two world championships, all our champions' (difficulty) scores were all very high, and their movements steady. "So our method of raising difficulty will not change.
